      <details>
        <summary>What exactly is considered a 'filler' episode in Boruto?</summary>
        <p>In Boruto, filler typically refers to episodes that do not adapt content directly from the official manga written by Ukyo Kodachi and Masashi Kishimoto. These episodes are usually created by the animation studio to allow the manga time to publish new chapters, preventing the anime from catching up too quickly.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is 'Anime Canon' the same thing as filler?</summary>
        <p>Not exactly. Boruto heavily utilizes 'Anime Canon'. These are episodes not in the manga, but they are officially approved by the creators and build upon the world, character development, and lore in ways that are considered canon to the anime's specific continuity. Many fans choose to watch these, unlike pure filler.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What percentage of Boruto is actually filler?</summary>
        <p>Depending on how strictly you define filler (including or excluding Anime Canon), the percentage varies wildly. Pure, inconsequential filler makes up roughly 15-20% of the series, but if you exclude all non-manga content, that number jumps to over 70%.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Will I be confused if I strictly only watch manga canon episodes?</summary>
        <p>Yes, occasionally. Because the anime integrates Anime Canon so heavily, characters introduced or developed in those arcs might suddenly appear in manga canon adaptations. You might lack context for their relationships or power sets if you skipped their introductory anime-only arcs.</p>
      </details>
